[14:23] <lateau> I'm wondering if you'll help me. I'm trying to convert Integer to Float with 'box'
[14:23] <lateau> I did this...$P0 = box 5; $N0 = $P0;
[14:23] <lateau> but print $P0 says just "5"
[14:23] <moritz> what else should it say?
[14:23] <pmichaud> printing floating point numbers doesn't force the decimal to appear
[14:23] <moritz> if you want a different stringification of your num, use printf
[14:24] <lateau> thank you!! i try printf
[14:24] <pmichaud> also
[14:24] <lateau> yub
[14:24] <pmichaud> note that your $P0 *is* an Integer
[14:24] <pmichaud> box 5 results in an Integer
[14:24] <moritz> just $N0 is a num
[14:24] <pmichaud> if you want the PMC to be a Float, use   box 5.0
[14:25] <lateau> are there any ways convert integer to floating number?
[14:26] <lateau> i red this, example's from http://docs.parrot.org/parrot/latest/html/docs/book/pir/ch04_variables.pod.html and it says boxing can low-level type conversion
[14:26] <moritz> $N0 = $I0
[14:26] <moritz> then your $N0 is a num
[14:26] <moritz> you can then to $P0 = $N0 if you really want it in a PMC
[14:27] <lateau> i see...
[14:27] <pmichaud> I think the article means that boxing enables you to convert from a native type to a boxed PMC type
[14:27] <pmichaud> i.e., it converts an int to an Integer, a num to a Float, or a string to a String
[14:28] *** preflex left
[14:28] <lateau> hmm...
[14:28] <lateau> $P0 = box 5
[14:28] <lateau> $S0 = $P0           # the string "5"
[14:28] <lateau> $N0 = $P0           # the number 5.0
[14:29] <lateau> i cannot understand this example clearly...
[14:30] <pmichaud> the first statement creates an Integer PMC from the int 5, and binds $P0 to that PMC
[14:30] <pmichaud> the second statement retrieves the string value of the PMC -- i.e., it gives us the string value of $P0 ("5")
[14:30] <pmichaud> the third statement retreives the floating point value of the PMC -- i.e., it gives us a num value of 5.0
